b'' b'}i need some advice on having someone ride pillion with me on my ninja.' b"}this will be the the first time i've taken anyone for an extended ride" b"}(read: farther than around the block we'll be riding some twisty," b'}fairly bumpy roads (the mines road-mt.hamilton loop for you sf bay areans).' b'' b'unless she is really adventurous, do not take her on this route for her' b"first extended ride! that's kinda like taking someone on a no-show 10-way" b'speed star competition as their first skydive.' b'' b"}this person is lbs. and fairly small, so i don't see weight as too much" b'}of a problem, but what sort of of advice should i give her before we go?' b'}i want her to hold onto me rather than the grab rail out back, and' b"}i've heard that she should look over my shoulder in the direction we're" b'}turning so she leans *with* me, but what else? are there traditional' b'' b'1) if the ninja has adjustable suspension, adjust it to a stiffer' b"setting so you don't bottom out in bumpy curves." b'' b'2) tell her the cardinal rules are:' b'' b'a) never ever ever ever put her feet down. not when you stop at a stop' b"sign, not when she thinks you're gonna crash, never. keep them on the" b'pegs until you tell her to get off the bike.' b'' b'b) she is to hold onto your waist. she should hold on tightly enough' b"that she won't slide off the bike if you twist the throttle a bit. and" b'(added bonus for you here), she should keep as close to your butt as' b"possible so quick stops don't make her slide into you and knock your" b'balls up onto the gas tank. you decide how best to word this.' b'' b"c) just stay perpendicular to the bike; straight up in the seat. don't" b'lean your body into curves, just go with the bike and stay perpendicular.' b"don't look over your shoulder.*" b'' b'3) remember at all times that you have a passenger on the back. that' b"means don't pop the clutch, and try to corner and stop smoother than" b"usual. be aware that if you jump on the brake, 